\subsection{Meridional Wind As A Function of Latitude And Altitude}
\begin{figure}[h!]
	\centering
	\includegraphics[width=0.7\linewidth]{../Meridional/contour/colormap.png}
	\caption{Colour Map}
	\label{m6}
\end{figure}
\noindent Viewing Figure \ref{m6} as differentials of latitudinal profiles of meridional wind across various altitudes, the complimentary cell-based observations made previously come into light. For most stronger bands of cell activity, there are corresponding winds near the tropopause in a the other direction. This pattern, combined with the clear differences in these latitudinal bands further corroborate the Hadley model. While previously hidden from view, we also notice the absence of prominent winds of this component in the middle altitudes. The $z$ component of wind is prominent in these regions. Figure \ref{m7} further describes these regions of northward and southward wind.
